It made me thin me of Jurassic Park's 3D filesystem browser: [fsn](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fsn). In fact, there is an upgraded version: [fsv](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_System_Visualizer).  
  
I just installed [fsv](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_System_Visualizer)... Not so easy. First, a little dependency hell: ./configure will start to complain about gtk-config. Install the gtk+ dev libraries through synaptic. Then, the gtkgl bindings, then the Mesa libraries... and the one who kept it from configuring: install freeglut-dev. Configure, make make install and here you go, although after the hassle, I don't recommend it: go for one of the other two. They are all just eye candy, after all.  

  

[![3d filesystem browser](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQHcblVI/AAAAAAAABN0/Mp32rZrmeW4/s400/fsvAnETF.png "3d filesystem browser")](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQHcblVI/AAAAAAAABN0/Mp32rZrmeW4/s1600-h/fsvAnETF.png)  
Jurassic Park-like: [fsv](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File_System_Visualizer)  

  

And the easier to install, in fact is [tdfsb](http://www.determinate.net/webdata/seg/tdfsb.html) (although it just looks strange... three D file system browser, easy to remember!). It has some nice points, and it looks pretty good too, in fact I don't know which I find more "fun", [tdfsb](http://www.determinate.net/webdata/seg/tdfsb.html) or [XCruiser](http://xcruiser.sourceforge.net/).  

  

[![3d filesystem browser](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQlcVAXI/AAAAAAAABOE/8o9MZinxXYM/s400/TDFSBhome.png "3d filesystem browser")](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQlcVAXI/AAAAAAAABOE/8o9MZinxXYM/s1600-h/TDFSBhome.png) [![3d filesystem browser](http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQeCI0TI/AAAAAAAABN8/NZYIimynF9w/s400/tdfsbAnETF.png "3d filesystem browser")](http://4.bp.blogspot.com/_f3d3llNlZKQ/SmiZQeCI0TI/AAAAAAAABN8/NZYIimynF9w/s1600-h/tdfsbAnETF.png)  
[tdfsb](http://www.determinate.net/webdata/seg/tdfsb.html)  

  

